          "id": "1.6",
          "title": "Compound Assignment Operators",
          "unit": 1,
          "source": "Unit1_Detailed_Tutorials.md",
          "body": "### What You Are Learning\n\nYou are learning shorthand forms for updating variables.\n\n### Operators\n\n```java\nx += y;   // x = x + y\nx -= y;   // x = x - y\nx *= y;   // x = x * y\nx /= y;   // x = x / y\nx %= y;   // x = x % y\n```\n\n### Worked Example\n\n```java\nint n = 10;\nn += 4;   // 14\nn *= 2;   // 28\nn %= 5;   // 3\n```\n\n### Increment and Decrement\n\n```java\nx++;\nx--;\n```\n\nThese mean:\n\n```java\nx = x + 1;\nx = x - 1;\n```\n\nAP questions may include `x++`, but avoid writing tricky code with prefix/postfix side effects.\n\n### Common Mistake\n\n```java\nint x = 5;\nx =+ 3;\n```\n\nThis is not `+=`. It assigns positive 3 to `x`.\n\nCorrect:\n\n```java\nx += 3;\n```\n\n### Practice\n\nTrace:\n\n```java\nint x = 6;\nx += 2;\nx *= 3;\nx -= 4;\n```\n\nAnswer:\n\n```text\nx = 20\n```"
